observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

a) Municipal Mayor ensure (i) the full or optimum utilization of the 20% DF in accordance with Section 5 of DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017; and (ii) the effective and efficient implementation of the projects to maximize the developmental benefits of the intended beneficiaries; 

b) Municipal Engineer (i) require concerned project engineer, officers and employees to be prudent in overseeing the timely implementation of PPAs under their responsibility; (ii) assist the MPDC in identifying which among those not yet completed nor started projects could be considered for possible realignment or reprogramming; (iii) provide satisfactory explanation as to why the projects were not yet completed or implemented; and (iv) provide complete information on the status of the projects funded by the 20% DF together with all the necessary details;

c) MPDC (i) ensure close coordination with the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant for proper monitoring of the implementation of the projects funded by the 20% DF and provide all the necessary information regarding the status of implementation of the projects for the timely preparation and submission of the Status Report of Government/Projects/Activities to the AT; (ii) ensure that the information provided in the Status Report of Government PPAs are complete before submitting to the AT; (iii) conduct intensive review of the continuing projects funded under the 20% DF to determine if the PPAs are still part of the vital needs of the Municipality otherwise reprogram the identified PPAs to other priority PPAs; and (iv) continue to identify projects that are doable and beneficial to the constituents; and

d) Municipal Budget Officer (i) explain as to why the balance of the identified 20% DF programs and projects were not properly presented in the SAAOB; (ii) locate the missing appropriation of ₱1,907,724.56 for the amortization of heavy equipment loan and water supply project loan; and (iii) henceforth ensure that the details of the PPAs and all other items indicated in the Annual Budget are properly presented and indicated in the SAAOB to avoid misleading information and possible missing appropriation.

We recommended that the:

a. Municipal Mayor (i) require end-user unit to prepare PPMP for consolidation of the BAC into an APP;

b. BAC prepare and submit APP for goods, services and infrastructure projects other than for Common-Use Supplies and Equipment in accordance with Sections 7.1 and 7.3.2 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184; (i) exert more diligence in the preparation of APP to ensure the accuracy and completeness of procurement needs based on approved PPMPs; and (ii) ensure that the items not available in PS-DBM are well supported by certification from the PS-DBM regarding stocks availability;

c.  BAC and GSO (i) procure common-use supplies at the PS-DBM as required by AO 17, DBM Circular Letter No. 2011-6 and the RIRR of RA No. 9184; and (ii) in case of non-availability of items in the PS-DBM, the procurement of common use goods should be procured in bulk quantities to avoid piecemeal purchases.

We recommended that the:

a) Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator comply with the requirements of DILG and DBM JMC No. 01 dated March 27, 2020 and include only those specifically allowed developmental projects and expenditures to be charged against the 20% DF;

b) Municipal Accountant submit supporting documents such as but not limited to (i) Valid Identification card (ID); (ii) certification from the Barangay that they are in need of assistance due to COVID-19 pandemic; (iii) cash assistance payroll similar to SAP which includes beneficiaries profile, witness, dated received and thumb mark portion; (iv) photo of beneficiary during actual receipt of the cash assistance; and (v) clear-cut policy/guidelines in the distribution of cash assistance and the criteria for the selection of beneficiaries;

c) SB, before enacting appropriation ordinance, ensure that items included therein are in accordance with existing and applicable laws, rules and regulations; and

d) Municipal Mayor submit explanation as to (i) why cash assistance amounting to ₱3,807,000.00 was granted and charged under the 20% DF on top of the SAP received from the DSWD; and (ii) why only nine out of 16 Barangays were given cash assistance.

We recommended that the:

a) Municipal Engineer submit the following:

• Project Management Procurement Plan and the APP showing the mode of procurement and the implementation of the said projects contracted through Pakyaw Labor Contract;

• Individual Program of Works and Detailed Cost Estimate to support the Pakyaw Labor Contract Cost and the required number of skilled worker/laborer; 

• Name of Project Facilitators per project and related documents that would prove his/her appointment as such duly approved by the Municipal Mayor;

• Certification or other related document that a formation or creation of Pakyaw Group was conducted;

• Letter of undertaking or application of Pakyaw Group to enter into Pakyaw Contract with the Municipality; and

• Detailed information of each individual/workers members of each Pakyaw Group for each Pakyaw Contract;

b) Municipal Engineer (i) explain why the Pakyaw Groups were allowed to claim 15% mobilization fee; and (ii) henceforth, ensure strict compliance with the guidelines and provisions of Appendix 1 of RA 9184 in the implementation of infrastructure projects by administration.

We recommended that the:

a) Municipal Accountant revise and resubmit the Notes to the Financial Statement and include the required information as provided by COA Circular No. 2012-002 and 2014-002;

b) MPDO and LDRRMO cause the immediate submission of LDRRMFIP for CY 2020 including in a separate caption, all unexpended fund from previous years’, duly received by the Office of the Civil Defense (OCD) and the DILG-LGOO as required by Sections 5.1.2 and 5.1.6 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 and Section 12 (c) (7) of the Philippine Disaster Risk Reduction Management Act of 2010 or RA No. 10121. Likewise, ensure timely preparation of LDRRMFIP for the succeeding years and furnish a copy to the AT for audit guidance and reference;

c) Municipal Mayor (i) prioritize the creation of LDRRM Office including its personnel; and (ii) thereafter, instruct the Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO) to facilitate the hiring of the three-support staff in compliance with Section 12 of RA No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1 dated April 04, 2014; and

d) LDRRMO secure fidelity bond from the Bureau of Treasury in accordance to Section 4.2 of Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 dated August 6, 2009.

We recommended that:

a. Municipal Administrator (i) cause strict adherence to the provisions set forth under COA Circular No. 77-61 to properly control the utilization of fuel; and (ii) require the officers/department concerned to completely put all the details and necessary information such as date of document, delivery terms, date of receipt of supplier in the PO and NOA, date of inspection and acceptance in the IAR. This should apply to all accounting forms and documents being used in all the Municipality’s financial transactions; 

b. Municipal Engineer prepare and submit the PPMP to the BAC in order to determine the mode of implementation and procurement of certain projects;

c. BAC (i) strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in all government procurement particularly on procurement thru public bidding; (ii) for SVP, ensure that the amounts are within the threshold of ₱200,000.00 for a 3rd class Municipality; and (iii) require the suppliers to submit all the documentary requirements for alternative methods of procurement under SVP such as, Mayor’s/Business Permit, PhilGEPS Registrations Number, Income/Business Tax Return and Omnibus Sworn Statement to determine that the suppliers are eligible and qualified to transact business with the Municipality pursuant to Appendix A of Annex H of RA No. 9184; and

d. Municipal Accountant (i) submit to the AT the relevant basic documentary requirements lacking in the sampled DVs for verification and audit; and (ii) exercise caution in ensuring the completeness and propriety of supporting documents before processing claims for payment as part of its internal audit service.

We recommended that the:

a. Municipal Mayor ensure that all procurements of the Municipality are conducted through public bidding as mandated under R.A.  No.  9184 and its IRR, unless justified by the conditions provided under Rule XVI of the IRR as recommended by the BAC. Alternative methods of procurement shall be resorted to only in highly exceptional cases provided for in R.A. No. 9184; 

b. BAC (i) explain the noted lapses in the conduct of procurement of CSM; (ii) ensure that there are PPMPs and APPs before conducting procurement; and (iii) strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in all government procurement to adhere to the principles of transparency, competitiveness, accountability, equity, efficiency, and economy; 

c. Municipal Administrator require the officers/department concerned to completely put all the details and necessary information such as date of document, delivery terms, date of receipt of supplier in the PO, date of inspection and acceptance in the IAR and delivery terms and place of delivery of goods in the CA. This should apply to all accounting forms and documents being used in all the Municipality’s financial transactions; and

d. Municipal Accountant (i) submit to the AT the relevant basic documentary requirements lacking in the sampled DVs for verification and audit; and (ii) exercise caution in ensuring the completeness and propriety of supporting documents before processing claims for payment as part of its internal audit service.

We recommended that the :

Municipal Mayor, through the MDRRM Council, ensure that the LDRRMFIP, which should include the PPAs to be funded by the previous years unexpended MDRRM Fund, be prepared and updated annually and incorporated in the annual investment Plan; and;
Prospectively, the Municipal Mayor and the official concerned conduct a thorough planning in the preparation of the LDRRMFIP with due consideration on the necessity and feasibility of the PPAs thus, ensuring its proper implementation.
